http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA043/Advanced+Searching?clicked=jirahelp#AdvancedSearching-ReservedCharacters claims:

{quote}
If you wish to use these characters in queries, you need to:

- surround them with quote-marks (you can use either single quote-marks (') or double quote-marks (")); and
- precede them with two backslashes.

For example: summary ~ "\\[example\\]" 
{quote}

So, to search for version "4.3 - EAP", one would have to enter:
{noformat} 
fixVersion = "4\\.3\\ -\\ EAP"
{noformat} 

However, this results in an error:
{noformat} 
The value '4\.3\ -\ EAP' does not exist for the field 'fixVersion'.
{noformat} 

Correct is to use quoted strings, but NOT a double backslash:
{noformat} 
fixVersion = "4.3 - EAP"
{noformat}

_Special thanks to the customer and developer Jens Doll. Technical description and impact analysis is quoted from him_
*Technical description:*
{quote}
The semantics of the above mentioned method is stated in the Java doc of the interface com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.renderer.JiraRendererPlugin:
{code}
/**
  * This allows the renderer to perform a transformation on the submitted edit value before
  * storing the value in the system. This can be useful if the value being submitted is
  * a different format (i.e. html markup that the edit control generates), than the system
  * expects to store (i.e. wiki markup). <b>NOTE: this method need not do anything if the
  * system is happy to store the value the edit control produces.<b>
  *
  * @param editValue is the value produced by the edit control.
  * @return the value in a form that the system expects to store.
  */
public Object transformFromEdit(Object editValue);´
{code}

But as stated, the CustomFieldImpl class disrespects the return value of the function transformFromEdit() and thus making this method completly worthless.
The excerpt from CustomFieldImpl.java shows this:
{code}
private Object processValueThroughRenderer(FieldLayoutItem fieldLayoutItem, Object value) {
  // ..
    rendererManager.getRendererForType(rendererType).transformFromEdit(value);
  // ..
  return value;
}
{code}

Interestingly other field implementations do indeed respect the return value. As example DescriptionSystemField.java is shown here:
{code}
public void updateIssue(FieldLayoutItem fieldLayoutItem, MutableIssue issue, Map fieldValueHolder) {
  // ..
    // give the renderer a change to transform the incomming value
    String desc = (String)rendererManager.getRendererForType(rendererType).transformFromEdit(getValueFromParams(fieldValueHolder));
    if (TextUtils.stringSet(desc))
      issue.setDescription(desc);
    else
      issue.setDescription(null);
}
{code}

A fix for this would be just adding {{value =}} in CustomFieldImpl.java before the call to the method. Resulting in something that looks like:
{code}
private Object processValueThroughRenderer(FieldLayoutItem fieldLayoutItem, Object value) {
  // ..
    value = rendererManager.getRendererForType(rendererType).transformFromEdit(value);
  // ..
  return value;
}
{code}

Note that this bug might be in more versions than the one stated here, 4.2.2 and 4.3 are the version where the bug was confirmed within the source.
{quote}

*Impact analysis*
{quote}
As for the impact analysis:
* For any vanilla JIRA installation (this means a out-of-the-box installation with no additional plug-ins whatsoever) the impact is negligible, since no renderer initially shipped with JIRA rely on this feature. (For example, the "Wiki Style Renderer" will just store the contents of the field as entered by the user in the database with no transformations applied.)  
This is probably the reason why this bug was never discovered.
* As it comes to plug-in developers this may render (huh!) some custom developed renderer implementations impossible since a server side transformation from returned values is not possible without this feature. One possible way to circumvent this is to apply all transformation that are necessary for a renderer with Javascript on the client side (in the HTML document, so to speak). But this makes an implementation of an renderer rely on Javascript to be enabled in the browser and thus effectivly prevents any [unobtrusive Javascript|http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unobtrusive_JavaScript] implementations.
{quote}

*Steps to reproduce the problem*
Jens Doll has created us a plug-in which has a renderer which is simply supposed to change the characters from lowercase to upper case. While it works as expected on System Fields, such as description, it does not work on custom fields:
* !create issue.PNG!

* !view issue.PNG!

The fix for JRA-21004 introduced the property 'jira.paths.set.allowed' which must be true to change the attachment settings.

Then we applied the fix for JRA-22493 which says it's cumulative - however, now the 'jira.paths.set.allowed=true' property is ignored and JIRA treats it like the property is set to false when we try to modify the attachment settings.

I've proven that 'jira.paths.set.allowed=true' by using a velocity processed message field to display the value of {code}jira.paths.set.allowed = $applicationProperties.getDefaultString("jira.paths.set.allowed"){code} (shows jira.paths.set.allowed = true).

I think that the change to JiraWebActionSupport.class for the 21004 fix:
{code}  public boolean isPathsAllowedToBetSet()
  {
    return new DangerousPathsChecker(getApplicationProperties()).isPathsAllowedToBetSet();
  }{code}
has been omitted from the version in the 22493 fix.

We've not spotted this sooner because we had jira.paths.set.allowed set to false until now as recommended but now we want to change the attachment settings.

Could you provide a version of JiraWebActionSupport.class with both fixes in so we can patch our patch?

Thanks.

