Currently you can only specify one import id prefix in the jira-application.properties file. However, we are importing and retiring two different systems into one JIRA installation in the near future and have a need to have two import id prefixes for two different projects. Is there a way to have two import ids and base them on which project the issue originates from?

For example, if I configured this field to work with Bugzilla all links on both custom fields pertaining to different systems would both point to Bugzilla. This would be fine if we only imported issues from Bugzilla, but now all links in my other Bug Import Id field also point to Bugzilla.

Hi Atlassian,

We have some workflows (probably created before 3.12) which do not show a modification date when "Workflows" is clicked in the Administrator menu. 

Now the new "View Workflow" feature does not work with issues related to such workflows. Each time "View Workflow" is clicked just en empty window is shown. If one creates a draft and publishes it the workflow state of the issue is displayed correctly.

I guess the reason is this code in CachingWorkflowImageManagerImpl.java
{code}   
        /*
            currently workflow.isDefault() negates workflowUpdated != null, however, if we ever ship other workflows
            with JIRA, they may have a null updated date like the default workflow does now
             */
            if (workflow.isDefault() || (workflowUpdated != null && !imageUpdated.before(workflowUpdated))) {
                //we have a valid cache image
                cacheIsValid = true;
            }
{code}   
For workflows without updated time cacheIsValid returns false and as such nothing is shown
   
Best regards,
Dieter

